(2.) In the next place then; whereas 'tis noted by diligent Obervers, that there is a wonderfull diverity in everal Countries, and even in the ame Countrey at everal ditant times, of thoe raging Dieaes, that Phyicians agree in calling
the Plague, (whence it happens that uch Medicins or Methods of curing as are in one Plague uccesfull, as Phlebotomy, Purging, &c. do oftentimes in another prove dangerous, if not mortal) whereas (I ay) this great variety has been oberv'd in Plagues; it may be fairly accounted for, by the great number and diverity that has been actually found, or may be reaonably uppo'd, in the numerous Minerals, and other Bodies that nature has lay'd up in the Subterraneal Regions: epecially if we conider, that the number of uch Bodies may be much increas'd and diverified, by the various combinations which may be made of them, not onely by caualties, but by the action of Subterraneal Fires, and aetuaries, and mentruums, uch as I have elewhere hewn to be lodg'd beneath the turf or uperficies of the Earth. And the acending Corpucles of thoe Mineral Bodies, being mot of them olid and ubtile, may produce in the Bloud;
and o in the Body, far more odd, and violent Symtomes, than the peccant Humours that ue to beget ordinary Dieaes. Which may be one reaon, and perhaps the chief, why the ancient Heathens, and Hippocrates himelf, acknowledg'd in Petilential Dieaes < in non-Latin alphabet > , omewhat of Divine, urpaing ordinary Nature.

THAT the Motion of the Air that accompanies Sounds may be propagated to great Ditances, and yet make coniderable Impreions on the Bodies it finds there, dipos'd to admit its Action, may be notably confirm'd, by a Phaenomenon I have met with, in the learned Mathematician Borellus, who relates it upon his own knowledge, and not undeervedly magnifies it: which I hall therefore recite in his
own Words. Borel. de vi Percuionis. Prop. CXI.Aderam (ays he) Tauromenii Siciliae, quando Aetna mons eruptionem quandam effecerat propè Ennam, urbem fere 30. Milliaria à Tauromenio ditantem, tunc vicibus interpolatis eruptiones ingentes ignis vorago efficiebat, grandi ono & trepitu, & tunc omnia Tauromenii aedificia, tremore concutiebantur, in quo Circumtantiam notatu digniimam obervavi: cilicet, quòd domus & aedificia quae directè expoita erant propectui ejudem voraginis, vehementiimè concutiebantur; reliquae verò domus, quae conpectu voraginis privabantur, atis lentè & leniter tremorem efficiebant. Upon which matter of fact he thus argues: Profectò, i hujumodi tremor factus fuiet à concuione & reilitione oli Tauromenitani, omnes domus aequè concuae fuient, & aequali tremore agitatae, ita ut non poit conpectus voraginis tam inignem & evidentem inaequalitatem tremoris procreare;
igitur neceariò à tremore ejudem aëris incuo in parietibus domorum liberè percuiones excipientum, agitatio illa efficiebatur. Videas hinc, (infers he) quanta oni ad 30 milliarium ditantiam efficacia it.

THAT Motion may be propagated far, through Bodies of differing Natures, may be inferr'd from what is mention'd in this Chapter, epecially about Earthquakes. But becaue it may reaonably be upected, that the Active Matter which produces thoe tupendious Motions, is dipers'd into divers Places, and may be of coniderable Extent, I hall here ubjoin, out of the Eloquent Famianus Strada, an Intance, which is much the mot memorable to my purpoe that I remember to have met with in Hitory;


to manifet to how great an extent a Motion excited in a very narrow compas, perhaps but a very few fathom quare, may be propagated through differing Mediums, and one of them as olid as Earth. This famous Hitorian then, having decrib'd a tupendious Work, that had been with great skill and care made by the Prince of Parma, to keep the City of Antwerp, which he cloely beieged, from being reliev'd by the River Scheldt (which, though not broad, is deep) proceeds to relate, that an Engineer, who was a great Mater in his Art, having undertaken to detroy this great Work with a Veel (which I think we may call a Floating Mine) fraught with Gunpowder, Fireworks, &c. perform'd it with o tragical a ucces, that ome Spanih Officers that were preent, reckon'd 800. to have been kill'd outright, beides a great number that were wounded and maim'd. But that Part of the Narrative which comes home to our preent


purpoe, is deliver'd in thee Words.
